This package contains the data release v1.0 of the Lyman-alpha Tomography IMACS Survey
(LATIS), which is described in the paper "LATIS Data Release: ~4200 Spectra of z~2-3
Galaxies, Redshifts, and IGM Tomography Maps" by Newman et al (2025) in ApJS.

This data release is complete and no further releases are planned. However, we assign a
version number to allow for any future corrections or possible expansions. A Jupyter
Python notebook is included with examples of how to load and manipulate the data.

If you make use of these data, please cite the aforementioned Newman et al (2025)
and the survey paper (Newman et al 2020, ApJ 891, 147).

==========================================================================================
REDSHIFT CATALOG
File: latis_zspec.fits (FITS table, 7408 rows)
==========================================================================================
Description of columns:
- name (string)
  Target name in format DX-N, where N is an integer and DX = D1, D2 (COSMOS), or D4.
- field (string)
  Field in which the target lies. This is the first two characters of the name.
- RA, Dec (float, units of deg)
  Coordinates from the CFHTLS T0007 catalog in D1 and D4 and Ilbert et al (2009) catalog
  in COSMOS. In some cases, coordinates were adjusted to the surface brightness peak.
- zqual (int)
  Redshift quality flag. 4 = very high confidence, 3 = high confidence, 2 = low
  confidence, 1 = single emission line, 0 = no redshift. See the ApJS paper for
  confidence levels.
- z (float)
  Redshift; see the ApJS paper for estimates of random and systematic uncertainties. For
  all targets with zqual < 3, z is set to NaN. For all stars, z is set to 0.
- isqso (bool)
  If True, the spectrum was modeled using the QSO templates as described in Newman
  et al (2020). Other high-z sources were modeled using LBG templates.
- isstar (bool)
  If True, the source is identified as a star.
- manualz (bool)
  If True, the redshift was not determined through LBG/QSO spectrum fitting. As discussed
  in the ApJS paper, this is the case for low-z galaxies, stars, and some QSOs and AGN.
- badredux (bool)
  If True, the spectrum is substantially affected by data reduction problems. Although a
  redshift might still be obtained, quantitative analysis of spectra should exclude
  these sources.
- tomo (bool)
  If True, the sight line was used for IGM tomography.
- brionly (bool)
  If True, the target was observed only on the bright-target masks intended for poor
  weather. These masks do not cover the full survey area and do not reach a uniform
  depth. It is recommended to exclude these targets if mapping galaxy densities.
- adc_corr (bool)
  If True, some of the exposures of this target were obtained with an incorrectly
  operating ADC, and spectra were corrected as described in Section 3.3 of the paper.
- z2 (float)
  Redshift of foreground absorption identified via multiple H I or metal transitions.
  If 'two galaxies' is present in the comments field, then z2 is a second galaxy
  redshift identified in the same spectrum. See ApJS paper.
- rmag (float)
  Aperture r-band AB magnitude, corrected for point-source losses and Galactic
  extinction. For sources of photometry, see Newman et al (2020), Section 3.2.
- u-g, g-r (float) 
  u-g and g-r colors used for target selection. A lower limit is given in cases of
  a non-detection in u. See Newman et al (2020).
- comments (string)
  Comments based on visual inspection of spectra. These may contain specific phrases,
  such as 'AGN' or 'two galaxies', with specific meanings discussed in the ApJS paper.


==========================================================================================
SPECTRA
File: latis_spectra.fits (FITS table)
==========================================================================================
All one-dimensional spectra are provided in a single FITS table, whose rows are in the
same order as latis_zspec.fits. Description of columns:
- name (string)
  Same as in latis_zspec.fits.
- wave (1222 x float32)
  Wavelength in Angstrom, in vacuum. This array is identical in every row but is repeated
  for convenience.
- flux (1222 x float32)
  Flux densities f_nu in microJansky. Please note that, as discussed in the ApJS paper,
  the spectra have *NOT* been corrected for slit losses, non-photometric conditions, or
  other phenomena with an approximately gray effect on the flux normalization. The
  flux densities are typically ~2x smaller than photometric measurements. Therefore
  absolute fluxes *should not be used*. Masked pixels are set to NaN.
- error (1222 x float32)
  1 sigma uncertainties in f_nu.
- model (1222 x float32)
  The LBG/QSO best-fit spectral model. In the Lya forest, the mean flux has been divided
  out of the templates, so this model represents the unabsorbed continuum.
- model_mfr (1222 x float32)
  The same model, but the Lya forest region has a continuum shape adjusted by mean flux
  regularization (MFR) *and* is multiplied by the mean flux <F(z)>. Therefore the Lya
  transmission fluctuation is delta_F = flux / model_mfr - 1.
- absmask (1222 x bool)
  Where True, this array indicates high-EW lines in the Lya forest that were identified
  and excluded from the tomography analysis.


==========================================================================================
TARGET SAMPLING AND SPECTROSCOPIC SUCCESS RATES
Files: latis_tsr.fits and latis_ssr.fits (multi-extension FITS)
==========================================================================================
Each FITS file has an extension for each survey field containing a map of the relative
TSR or SSR, including WCS. The target sampling rate (TSR) is the fraction of objects in
the parent catalog that were observed. The spectroscopic success rate (SSR) is the
fraction of observed objects for which a high-confidence z_spec was obtained. These values
consider only the main masks, not the bright-target masks (sources identified by the
'brionly' flag above), which cover the survey area very non-uniformly. For the TSR map,
the parent sample was defined by the candiate QSOs, plus the candidate LBGs in the range
r_min < r < 24.8 (see ApJS paper). The absolute value of the TSR will vary strongly
with magnitude, but its relative angular variation, which is the critical quantity for
many applications (e.g., overdensities, clustering), should not. These maps were initially
described and visualized in Newman et al (2024), ApJ 961, 27.


==========================================================================================
LYMAN-ALPHA TRANSMISSION FLUCTUATIONS: DELTA_F PIXELS
Files: D{1,2,4}_pix.dat (binary format), D{1,2,4}_sightline_ids.dat
==========================================================================================
The D{1,2,4}_pix.dat files contain the measured Lyman-alpha transmission fluctuations delta_F
in each field (note D2 = COSMOS) in the format required by the "dachshund" Wiener filtering
code (see https://github.com/caseywstark/dachshund). The format is binary and consists of
a series of double-precision floats (little endian). The first 5 floats contain X, Y, Z,
delta_F_error, and delta_F for the first pixel. See the ApJS paper for the definition
of the X, Y, Z coordinate system. Here delta_F_error refers to the sigma_tot of the
ApJS paper, which consists of random and continuum errors added in quadrature. The
next 5 floats correspond to the next pixel, and so on. The D1, D2, and D4 fields contain
163823, 244883, and 60302 pixels, respectively. The files can be accessed in Python
as follows:
   import numpy as np
   pixels = np.fromfile('D1_pix.dat').reshape((-1, 5))
   X, Y, Z, dFerror, dF = pixels.T
The D{1,2,4}_sightline_ids.dat files contain the information needed to associate
each delta_F pixel with the spectrum from which it was derived. These files can be
loaded as follows:
   ids = np.fromfile('D1_sightline_ids.dat', dtype=int)
In this example, 'ids' has the same length as the 'dF' array, and its values index the
rows of the latis_zspec.fits table.


==========================================================================================
IGM TOMOGRAPHY MAPS
Files: D{1,2,4}_map.fits and D{1,2,4}_map_unnorm.fits (multi-extension FITS)
==========================================================================================
The files D{1,2,4}_map.fits are the same as those distributed along with Newman et al
2025, "LATIS: A Sample of IGM-Selected Protoclusters and Protogroups at z~2.5", at the
separate Zenodo record https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.15200365.

Three multi-extension FITS files contain maps for fields D1, D2 (COSMOS), and D4.

Extention DELTA_F_NORM contains the map of the Lyman-alpha transmission fluctuation
delta_F, smoothed with a 3D Gaussian having sigma = 4 cMpc/h, and normalized by the
standard deviation sigma_map of the resulting map. LATIS analysies have almost always
used these smoothed and normalized maps.

Extension ERR_DELTA_F_NORM contains, for each voxel, the 1 sigma uncertainty in the
smoothed delta_F / sigma_map. These are estimated from the mock surveys, as described at
the end of Section 2 of Newman et al 2025.

The three axes of the 3D map arrays correspond, in order, to the X, Y, and Z coordinates
described in the ApJS paper. Voxel sizes are (1 cMpc/h)^3. Note that the Z axis is
483 voxels long in every field.

Extension Z is a 1D array containing the redshift of voxels along the Z axis. Note a 1D
array is sufficient because the conversion does not depend on the transverse position.
Extensions RA and DEC are 3D arrays, with the same dimensions as the map, containing the
celestial coordinates of each voxel in deg. (The mapping from voxel to celestial
coordinates depends on redshift, because we use a varying angular diameter distance to
convert from angles to cMpc/h.) Coordinates here refer to voxel centers.

The files D{1,2,4}_map_unnorm.fits contain the extensions DELTA_F and ERR_DELTA_F
instead of DELTA_F_NORM and ERR_DELTA_F_NORM. These extensions contain delta_F and its
1 sigma uncertainty, without normalization by sigma_map. The contents of the other arrays
are the same.

As discussed in the ApJS paper, there is a non-trivial relationship between the
reconstructed delta_F in these maps and the expected transmission fluctuation.


==========================================================================================
MOCK IGM TOMOGRAPHY MAPS FROM MDPL2
Files: mocks/D{1,2,4}_NN.fits where NN = 00, 01, ..., 99 (multi-extension FITS)
==========================================================================================
For each survey field, the data release contains 100 mock IGM tomography maps produced
within the MDPL2 simulation snapshot at z=2.535.

Extension DELTA_F_REC contains a 3D array of the mock-observed delta_F, smoothed with a
sigma = 4 cMpc/h gaussian. The shape of the array follows the observed maps described
above.

Extension DELTA_F_TRUE contains a 3D array of the "true" delta_F, built directly from a
dense grid of noiseless sightlines without applying a Wiener filter, as described in
the ApJS paper.

The x, y coordinates within the MDPL2 simulation box that correspond to the lower-left
corner of each map (i.e., the lower edge of the first voxel) are given in header keywords
X0 and Y0, which have units of cMpc/h. The size of the simulation box is (1000 cMpc/h)^3
and the subvolumes are chosen to be mostly non-overlapping. The lower-left corner
always has a simulation z coordinate of 0. These coordinates are necessary, for example,
to compare delta_F to the halo overdensity computed from MDPL2 halo catalogs.


